  <section><div class="wrap">
    <div class="pillar"><h3>Defense innovation</h3><p>From an elite Israel Air Force technology unit to a theory of cyber-power, I read where security and defense innovation actually comes from — and how it becomes advantage. Not the hype; the edge.</p></div>
    <div class="pillar"><h3>AI</h3><p>AI can deliver insight, decision support, and autonomy. But throwing a frontier model at a broken system only hides the structural causes. Making AI work is an organizational problem, not a model problem — regulation, culture, politics, and incentives are the real terrain. I help governments and investors reorganize around AI, so the promise becomes outcomes.</p></div>
    <div class="pillar"><h3>Capacity building</h3><p>National strategies, sectoral resilience, and a proprietary cyber capability-maturity method — built to leave durable capability behind, not another report.</p></div>
  </div></section>
  <section><div class="wrap">
    <p class="eyebrow">First principles</p>
    <p class="lead">The doctorate isn't decoration. It's the discipline to reason from first principles when the playbooks don't fit — to see the whole system, separate signal from noise, and, as Michael Porter put it, decide what not to do. Where the ground shifts and the stakes are national, that rigor is the difference between motion and progress.</p>
  </div></section>
